\par }\pard\plain \s20\qc\sb100\sa100\keepn\nowidctlpar\outlinelevel3\adjustright \b\fs28\lang2057 {FORMAT DETAILS:
\par }\pard\plain \sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {Because this format is sourced on IRIX, the word format is bit[15..0]. Fetched words will have to be swapped for PC based readers. 
\par First, a 10-byte header: 
\par }\pard\plain \s32\nowidctlpar\tx0\tx959\tx1918\tx2877\tx3836\tx4795\tx5754\tx6713\tx7672\tx8631\adjustright \f2\fs20\lang2057 {BYTES           DESCRIPTION
\par 
\par   0, 1          Width -- X res in pixels.
\par   2, 3          Height -- Y res in pixels.
\par   4, 5          X offset -- unused (obsolete, but still present).
\par   6, 7          Y offset -- unused (obsolete, but still present).
\par   8, 9          Bits per pixel -- always 0x18, or 8 bits each of red, green,
\par                 and blue (they have no other supported bit depth at this time)
\par }\pard\plain \sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {The pixels are then run-length encoded in 4 byte packets on a per-scanline basis, starting with the top scanline in the image. Individual runs do not extend beyond a single scanline. 
\par }\pard\plain \s32\nowidctlpar\tx0\tx959\tx1918\tx2877\tx3836\tx4795\tx5754\tx6713\tx7672\tx8631\adjustright \f2\fs20\lang2057 {PACKET
\par BYTE            RANGE           DESCRIPTION
\par 
\par   0             0x01 - 0xFF     Run length - number of pixels in succession
\par                                 with given RGB.
\par   1             0x00 - 0xFF     Blue component.
\par   2             0x00 - 0xFF     Green component.
\par   3             0x00 - 0xFF     Red component.
\par }\pard\plain \sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {Here's a sample: 
\par }\pard\plain \s32\nowidctlpar\tx0\tx959\tx1918\tx2877\tx3836\tx4795\tx5754\tx6713\tx7672\tx8631\adjustright \f2\fs20\lang2057 {00000000  0008 0006 0000 0005 0018 08FF 0000 08CC
\par 00000020  0000 0899 0000 0866 0000 0833 0000 0800
\par 00000040  0000
\par }\pard\plain \sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {This sample describes an 8 x 6 r
amp from blue (at the top of the image) to black. The 10 byte header is easy enough (note the obsolete offset info of 0, 5): [0008 0006 0000 0005 0018]. This is followed by [08FF 0000], which is 8 pixels of [FF 00 00], or pure blue. All 8 bytes of the fir
st line are satisfied, so the next packet begins the next scan line: [08CC 0000], and so on. 
\par }\pard\plain \s20\sb100\sa100\keepn\nowidctlpar\outlinelevel3\adjustright \b\fs28\lang2057 {FORMAT BACKGROUND:
\par }\pard\plain \sb100\sa100\nowidctlpar\adjustright \lang2057 {
